ce:section.ce:para:
Carbon dots treatment increased the shoot dry weight (9.7%), root dry weight (24.1%), plant height (4.6%), and total chlorophyll content (33.2%) in comparison to the control. Cadmium (50 mg kg−1) treatment decreased shoot dry weight, plant height, and chlorophyll content, 13.6, 14.4, and 9.5%, respectively, compared to control (Fig. 4
                        ). The Cd + CD treatment increased the shoot dry weight (0.8%) and root dry weight (2.5%) and shoot chlorophyll content (24.3%) compared to the Cd treatment (Fig. 5
                        ).

By adding carbon dots to soil samples, the amount of dissolved organic carbon increased significantly (77.9%) compared to the control. The amount of dissolved organic carbon in the two treatments Cd and Cd + CD also increased by 18.3% and 64.4%, respectively, compared to the control (Fig. 6
                        ). The presence of carbon dots in the soil caused a significant increase (38.3%) in microbial respiration, while the presence of cadmium reduced microbial respiration by 23.6%. The Cd + CD treatment also caused a reduction (34.7%) in the Basal respiration compared to the control. Microbial biomass carbon also increased by 54.9% in the presence of carbon dots, and cadmium treatment showed a negative effect (14.9%). The Cd + CD treatment caused an increase of 24.2% in microbial biomass carbon compared to the Cd treatment (Fig. 7
                        ).
